caption: The place is basically dingy and smelly. The artifacts are poorly displayed and of low quality. The self importance is not warranted and ostentatious. The mix of Yemen , Ethiopia etc. Is chaotic and in a crowded setting. Not child friendly and definitely not recommended

AWESOME ! Magical place where high quality and unique exhibitions follow one another. Home Top of a brilliant and caring guide, with countless hats, knowledgeable about the Horn of Africa and the Red Sea...BIG favorite!
It's a very impressive place, I'm glad I went there. In addition, we were very well received by a specialist who was able to give us details on the objects present and their history.
A small, volunteer-run museum about Arabia Felix / Yemen, the area over which the Queen of Seba is said to have ruled. Quite an impressive collection and well presented for such an institution.

Really deplorable welcome Our host seems to have a hypertrophied ego very far from the humility of Theodore Monod Too bad, I would have liked to share my Yemeni experience. But this gentleman's self-importance discouraged me.

We are in front of the site Saturday November 26 at 4:20 p.m. it is noted open on the site, but everything is closed. I'm calling, it's an answering machine. In short, I moved from Dax on purpose, to no avail
Great, nevertheless the guide acted... AS IF I DIDN'T EXIST and then SHE PASSED BY ME! A little annoying but beyond this feeling, the place is worth it.
An exhibition space, founded by Théodore Monod with José-Marie Bel, who has the soul of their numerous travels to the Middle East and the Sahara.

An astonishing place full of charm. Many objects brought back from the expeditions and above all a lot of documentation allowing us to better understand Yemen and the complexity of the current situation.
A nugget! Diverse and exciting exhibitions. A big congratulations to the entire team of enthusiasts from this part of Africa!
Space run by volunteers who have a lot of merit in bringing this place to life, with very interesting documents. Go see them, they are worth it.
Superb dive into the kingdom of the Queen of Sheba thanks to Théodore Monod and José Marie Bel. Well done
